section.t:
 (section 5) describes seven
	questions to be answered in order to provide clear guidance
	about how and why a particular domain name is special. These
	seven questions can be broadly categorised as follows:


          impact on end-users;

          impact on applications;

          impact on name resolution APIs and libraries;

          impact on recursive resolvers;

          impact on authoritative DNS servers;

          impact on DNS server operators;

          impact on DNS registries and registrars.


        Answers to these seven questions provide guidance to
        various audiences on how to handle a special-use domain name
        once it has been registered. However, they are inadequate
        for determining whether a particular domain name qualifies
        as being special and should be included in the Registry.

At the time of writing, three top-level domain names reserved by inclusion in the Registry are used by name resolution protocols other than the DNS:
is used to refer to the host on which the name resolution takes place, without reference to the DNS;
is used by the Multicast DNS protocol specified in which is similar in some respects to the DNS, but which uses a different well-known port number and is limited to a particular multicast scope;
is used to construct names that designate anonymous hidden services reachable via the Tor network using onion routing.
The three name resolution protocols described above are different from the DNS, and the namespaces used in each naming scheme are also different (if similar, in some cases). The top-level label is hence effectively being used as a name resolution protocol identifier.
